1. e4 Nf6!? (1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bd3 c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 b6 { , etc, and so I decided to play Alekhine's Defense,
worried that it'd be hard to win in the Rubinstein. It's a guilty pleasure of
mine, and I noticed that my opponent had a terrible score against it, and
frequently played the Exchange Variation, which I really enjoy playing against. }) 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 (4. Nf3! { is the only move I'm all that
concerned about theoretically, after which I like to play the Larsen/Kengis
with } 4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 { , and so on. }) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6! { This is the
only move worth playing in my opinion, but only with 9...Bf5. } (5... exd6 { is recommended in a lot of the literature, but just acquiesces to a slight
disadvantage in a symmetrical structure and is not to my taste. }) 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3! { The dreaded Voronezh variation, which has caused Black a lot of
problems in this variation historically. } (7. Nf3 { is more natural, but after } 7... Bg7 8. Be3 O-O { none of White's choices are impressive: } 9. Be2 { is a very
natural and classical set-up, but is probably even dubious after the obvious } (9. h3 { If White decides to stop ...Bg4 Black gets good counterplay after } 9... Nc6 { and now: } 10. Be2 (10. b3?! { (stopping ...Nc4 as in below) } 10... d5 (10... f5!? $132) 11. c5 Nd7 12. Rc1 (12. Nxd5 Nxc5 { [%cal Gg7a1] }) 12... Nxc5! 13. dxc5 d4 $132) 10... Bf5 11. O-O d5! 12. c5 Nc4 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qa4 Bd3 15. Rfd1 Qe8!? $132 { L.Milman-A.Shabalov,
Philadelphia 2004 }) 9... Bg4 10. O-O Nc6 11. b3 d5! 12. c5 { [%cal Gb6d7,Gc3d5] } 12... Nc8 { , as Black
gets a tempo up version of the game. M.Aigner-H.Nakamura, Las Vegas 2007,
which continued } 13. h3 { [%cal Gg4f3] } 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 15. Rc1 N8e7 16. Ne2 Nf5 17. Bg4 Nh4 18. f4 h5 $15) 7... Bg7 { [%cal Gg7b2] } 8. Rc1! O-O 9. b3 { Now it's easier to see White's
opening idea - all the counterplay down the long diagonal is neutralized, and
Black has been denied ...Bg4. } 9... Bf5! { Extremely popular lately, and probably
the only playable move. } (9... Nc6?! { has historically been the move, but
illustrates another facet of the Voronezh, as after } 10. d5 Ne5 11. Be2! { +/=/+/-, Black's knight on e5 is in rough shape. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf2f4] }) 10. Nf3 (10. Be2 { can
