1. g3!? { I knew my opponent was playing the Dutch regardless - it's important
to have a sense of humor! } 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3!? { I have taken to really liking this line for White after seeing some
analysis by Christof Sielecki. But my opponent surprises me a bit later and I
mishandle it. Later in the season I have better luck with this move. } (6. d4 { is more usual, e.g. } 6... d6 7. Nc3 Ne4!? { This is the newest move (and
recommended by expert Simon Williams), but I was perhaps one of the first to
discover that } (7... a5 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qc2! { always seemed clearly better for
White to me }) (7... Qe8) 8. Nxe4! fxe4 9. Nd2 d5 10. f3 Nc6 (10... e3? 11. Nb1 dxc4 12. Bxe3 Bf6 13. Na3 $16) 11. fxe4 Rxf1+ 12. Kxf1! dxc4 13. Nf3 $16 { of E.Tomashevsky-Z.Rahman, FIDE World Cup 2015, is simply way better for
White - it has been tested quite a few times now, and the first player scores
really well. }) 6... d6 7. d4 a5!? { This is not a move I looked at in my
preparation, but it's tricky in that the inclusion of b3 and ...a5 makes the
usual scheme of Nxe4 and f3 bad here, which I failed to understand. } (7... Qe8 8. Bb2 Qh5 9. Nc3! $14) (7... Ne4 8. Bb2 Bf6 9. Nbd2 Nc6 10. Ne1! $14) 8. Nc3 Ne4 9. Nxe4? { This no longer works, unfortunately for me. I spent little
time here, as I knew the usual 7...Ne4 8.Nxe4 lines were good for White. } (9. Bb2! Nxc3 (9... Bf6 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Nc6 12. e4 $14) 10. Bxc3 Qe8 11. Qd3! (11. Re1 Qh5 12. e4 f4 13. e5 d5 { +/=/~~ }) 11... Qh5 12. e4 f4 13. e5 d5 { F.Graf-T.Rendle, Hastings 2006 } 14. Ne1!? $146 { +/-/+/= }) 9... fxe4 10. Nd2 d5 11. f3 e3! { This is usually not good,
and as such, I missed it. } 12. Nb1 c5! $132 13. Bxe3 Bf6? (13... cxd4! 14. Bxd4 Nc6 15. Bb2 dxc4!? { is an interesting and better SF suggestion. }) 14. Na3?! Nc6 15. Nb5 cxd4 16. Nxd4 Qb6! { Now my opponent finds some strong,
and (at least for me) not super intuitive ways to grab the initiative. I
started using a lot of time here trying to solve my issues. } 17. Nc2 Qa6! (17... d4 { , after which I thought } 18. Bf2 e5 19. Ne1 $14 { would be about equal. }) 18. cxd5 (18. Nd4! dxc4 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Rc1 { as a
clearly better option, but how is any normal human being supposed to allow ...
c3 here? I thought my move was basically the only try. }) 18... Bxa1 19. Qxa1 (19. dxc6?! Bf6 20. f4 Rd8 $15) 19... exd5 20. f4 Qxe2 21. Bxd5+ Kh8 22. Rf2 Qb5 (22... Qh5 23. Bf3 Bg4 $17 { is apparently much better, though this move
isn't bad. }) 23. Bc4 Qf5 24. Re2 b5 { I didn't see this at all - clearly just
not my day. } 25. Nd4 Nxd4 26. Bxd4 bxc4 27. Bxg7+ (27. Re7!?) 27... Kg8 28. Bxf8 Qxf8 29. Qd4! { Computers will give the infamous 0.00 here,
but from a human perspective, it seems incredibly hard to draw this as White
given the incredibly weak light squares around the king, and even problems
along the first or second rank. } 29... Bg4 30. Re5 h6 31. Qxc4+ Qf7 32. Qe4 Rd8 33. Qe3 Rd1+ 34. Kf2 Rd7? (34... Qd7! $19 { was spotted by a few of the
observers live. }) 35. Rxa5 Qg6 36. Ra8+ Kh7 37. Qc3?? { I had very little time
on my clock here, less than a minute, and I simply missed Black's next, which
is incidentally the only win. } 37... Qb6+ 0-1


